<activity xml:id="act-uSubRecap">
    <title>Recapping <m>u</m>-Substitution</title>
    <introduction>
        <p>
            We're going to consider a few integrals, and work through each of the questions for all integrals.
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\displaystyle \int \left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{4-3x}}\right)\;dx</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\displaystyle \int x^2(5+x^3)^7\;dx</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\displaystyle \int \left(\frac{\sin(x)}{\cos(x)}\right)\;dx</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\displaystyle \int \left(xe^{-x^2}\right)\;dx</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                For each integral, explain why <m>u</m>-substitution is a good choice. How can you tell, just by looking at the integral, that this strategy will be a reasonable thing to try?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                For each integral, explain your choice of <m>u</m>, what that means for how we define <m>du</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                For each integral, is your definition of <m>du</m> present in the integrand function? How do you go about making this substitution when the integrand function isn't set up perfectly?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Finish the substitution and integration, and substitute back to the original variable.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
</activity>